Ready state 4 would indicate that you are done with your request. This example will show you the various levels of readyState.

    var xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();
    console.log(&#39;UNSENT&#39;, xhr.readyState); // readyState will be 0
    
    xhr.open(&#39;GET&#39;, &#39;/api&#39;, true);
    console.log(&#39;OPENED&#39;, xhr.readyState); // readyState will be 1
    
    xhr.onprogress = function () {
        console.log(&#39;LOADING&#39;, xhr.readyState); // readyState will be 3
    };
    
    xhr.onload = function () {
        console.log(&#39;DONE&#39;, xhr.readyState); // readyState will be 4
    };
    
    xhr.send(null);

More information can be found here https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/XMLHttpRequest/readyState

When using a callback, here is a simple function that takes in a username, and a callback function, this function will use setState to set the current state, then it will run its callback function, since I will call it after setState.

    function one(username, blah) {
       this.setState({
           username: username 
       })
       blah()
    } 
So now you have your function ready, it will take in a username setState and then run ANY function passed in when called.

    function two() {
     console.log(&#39;WOOOHOO We got a username and set state&#39;);
    }
    function three() {
     console.log(&#39;O joy we got a username&#39;);
    }
Now I will show you calling you function. 

    one(&#39;Bob&#39;, two) // Output: WOOOHOO We got a username and set state
    one(&#39;Bob&#39;, three) // O joy we got a username 

As you can see we are calling the same function &#39;one&#39; but the functions passed in are different in the two examples.

